Name: Disrupted Engine
Description: This spacesuit propulsion unit is disrupted and operating below the manufacturer's published performance levels.

Name: Spacesuit Thrusters Mk1
Description: Pilots using the standard spacesuit propulsion unit for extended distances are advised to have patience and an adequate supply of Oxygen.

Name: Spacesuit Thrusters Mk2
Description: It remains uncertain how the fashion for personal propulsion unit modifications first arose. However, the alarming increase in injuries from such "home-mods" led to the formalisation of standards for the Mk 2 spacesuit propulsion unit.\n\nThis widely applauded measure has radically reduced the accidental incineration rate across all known sectors.

Name: All-round Engine
Description:
Like most representative democracies, the Argon Federation prioritises crew survival in armed combat vessels over cost effectiveness. Since survivability is proportional to the ability to evade unwinnable situations, Argon engines feature powerful afterburners, providing ample boost for evasive manoeuvres, and the chance to return to the fight unscathed.

Shipowners who want to be ready for anything often choose the All-round class engine, which balances long-distance speed with localised acceleration capability.

Large, L-size engines may only be fitted to vessels of the corresponding size category.

The Mark I drive is the basic model.

Name: All-round Engine
Description:
Before the Fall of the Gates, a highly efficient engine type emerged from the Queendom's propulsion foundry, variants of which remain in use today. Its emphasis is on engaging Travel Mode instantly, as well as long boost durations. Combined, these offset the mediocre general thrust. Boron engines are incompatible with non-Boron vessels.

Shipowners who want to be ready for anything often choose the All-round class engine, which balances long-distance speed with localised acceleration capability.

Large, L-size engines may only be fitted to vessels of the corresponding size category.

The Mark I drive is the basic model.

Name: All-round Engine
Description:
Paranid propulsion foundries have long been known for designing the fastest engines commercially available. With mathematics and engineering being a matter of religious determination and national pride, they've maintained their edge for countless decades. Paranid engines excel at both speed and long-range operations.

Shipowners who want to be ready for anything often choose the All-round class engine, which balances long-distance speed with localised acceleration capability.

Large, L-size engines may only be fitted to vessels of the corresponding size category.

The Mark I drive is the basic model.

Teladi engines may seem unremarkable at first glance, but their extended boost duration and efficient travel drive optimisation suits them for both long and short-range transportation duty. While not combat-optimised, they're valued for their reliability and longevity.

Shipowners who want to be ready for anything often choose the All-round class engine, which balances long-distance speed with localised acceleration capability.

Small, S-size engines may only be fitted to vessels of the corresponding size category.

This drive is usually available in three editions, Marks I, II and III, indicating the level of performance upgrade.

Name: Combat Engine Mk3
Description:
Like most representative democracies, the Argon Federation prioritises crew survival in armed combat vessels over cost effectiveness. Since survivability is proportional to the ability to evade unwinnable situations, Argon engines feature powerful afterburners, providing ample boost for evasive manoeuvres, and the chance to return to the fight unscathed.

The Combat-class engine is optimised for high-burst delivery, and provides the acceleration and agility needed for battle situations.

Small, S-size engines may only be fitted to vessels of the corresponding size category.

This drive is usually available in three editions, Marks I, II and III, indicating the level of performance upgrade.

Description:
True to their warrior culture, Split engine design prioritises raw thrust above all else. Optimised for combat, these engines largely ignore safety considerations, sacrificing travel drive efficiency for superior manoeuvrability.
